      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, my apologies for the goblin slip-up! Let's get back to the baking essentials then. To determine if the temperature is the culprit, you'll want to use a reliable kitchen thermometer to check the actual temperature of your starter. Sourdough starters typically thrive at around 75°F (24°C), but even a few degrees off can affect their activity.\n\nIf the temperature is indeed correct, then it might be time to consider the flour type. Rye flour is a good choice for starters because it's rich in nutrients that feed the yeast and bacteria. However, if you're still not seeing any bubbling or growth, you might want to try a different flour, like whole wheat or all-purpose, to see if that encourages your starter to wake up. Just remember to keep everything else consistent, like the feeding schedule and the amount of flour and water you use.\n\nIf you're still having trouble, you might want to try feeding your starter with equal parts of flour and water, and then let it sit for a few hours before checking if there's any activity. Sometimes, a little patience and a bit of experimentation can help you find the right balance for your sourdough starter. Good luck, and may your baking endeavors be fruitful!",
