      "content": "Absolutely, starters can sometimes be a bit deceptive in their appearance. If your starter looks thick, it could be due to the flour absorbing more water than usual, or it might just be a sign that it's ready for a feed. Tiny bubbles can also be a sign of activity, even if they're not immediately noticeable. Sometimes, the bubbles are so small that they don't rise to the surface quickly, but they're still there, working away at the culture.\n\nIf you're concerned about the health of your starter, you can do a simple test. Take a small spoonful of your starter and mix it with a little bit of water. If it bubbles vigorously, it's a good sign that your culture is alive and well. If there's no reaction, you might need to give it another feed or check if the temperature is indeed consistent.\n\nRemember, sourdough starters can be a bit like a living creature; they have their own personalities and quirks. It might take a little while to get them to behave just the way you want, but with a bit of patience and attention, you'll have a bubbly, active culture ready for baking in no time. Keep at it, and don't hesitate to ask if you have more questions or need further guidance!",
